#1-1Reading the file.

#Jaehyun Song
# The data we got is from "Kaggle. It is repackaged data from  a newer compilation put together by the Berkeley Earth, which is affiliated with Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory. The Berkeley Earth Surface Temperature Study combines 1.6 billion temperature reports from 16 pre-existing archives.
# The year 1850 is the period when surface temperature observations began widely and is commonly used as the base year for the start of industrialization. Since 1850, the average global surface temperature has steadily risen, and by the end of 2017, it has risen by more than 1 degree compared to before the Industrial Revolution. In particular, after 1900, the upward trend was noticeable, and the warming trend was accelerated for a certain period of time, but there was also a period of global warming rest (or recess) where the upward trend stopped for a certain period of time. During the 1900-1950 and 1975-1997, warming accelerated, and during the 1950-1975 and 1998-2013 periods it stopped. It is suggested that long-term natural variability, such as Pacific Decadal Oscillation, can affect the acceleration and suspension of such warming.

#1-2 Cleaning and filtering data

#Jaehyun Song

# Erased the NA values.
data <- data %>% na.omit()

# There are 100 cities in our data. So we divided it to 25 cities to search roughly about their industrialization period so when it comes to visualization, it could be easier to compare.
all_cities <- unique(data$City)
part1_cities <- all_cities[1:25]
part2_cities <- all_cities[26:50]
part3_cities <- all_cities[51:75]
part4_cities <- all_cities[76:100]

part4_cities
##  [1] Rangoon          Rio De Janeiro   Riyadh           Rome            
##  [5] So Paulo       Saint Petersburg Salvador         Santiago        
##  [9] Santo Domingo    Seoul            Shanghai         Shenyang        
## [13] Singapore        Surabaya         Surat            Sydney          
## [17] Taipei           Taiyuan          Tangshan         Tianjin         
## [21] Tokyo            Toronto          Umm Durman       Wuhan           
## [25] Xian            
## 100 Levels: Abidjan Addis Abeba Ahmadabad Aleppo Alexandria Ankara ... Xian
# The column 'dt' had data about date, but the data type wasn't date. So we changed the data type,
# and sliced the data from 1860-01-01 because this is the point when there is not much NA values.
clean <- data %>% mutate(When = as.Date(dt, format="%Y-%m-%d")) %>% filter(When >= as.Date("1860-01-01"))

# By reading date data and extract month value, I made new column which explains the season. I used ifelse function.
yclean <- clean %>% mutate(year = year(When), month = month(When), season = ifelse(month==3|month==4|month==5,'Spring', 'Summer' ))
yclean$season <- ifelse(yclean$month==9| yclean$month==10| yclean$month==11 , 'Autumn',yclean$season )
yclean$season <- ifelse(yclean$month==12| yclean$month==1| yclean$month==2 , 'Winter',yclean$season )

# Asia city

AC1870 <- Asia_city %>%
  group_by(City) %>% filter(year==1870) %>%
  mutate(avg1870 = mean(AverageTemperature)) %>% na.omit()


AC2012 <- Asia_city %>%
  group_by(City) %>% filter(year==2012) %>%
  mutate(avg2012 = mean(AverageTemperature)) %>% na.omit()

AC <- Asia_city %>%
  group_by(City) %>% summarise(avg = mean(AverageTemperature),lon=unique(Longitude),lat=unique(Latitude)) %>%
  mutate(avg_diff = unique(AC2012$avg2012)-unique(AC1870$avg1870))

#2 Finding changes of temperature in every city.

#Jaehyun Song
# To check cities more efficiently, I processed data to produce the difference between highest average temperature per year and lowest of it. 
# Then by using arrange function, I could find cities that have big change in temperature. Then by dividing cities by continent, we chose about 7 cities in each continent which has big change and not.

#This is a code for finding cities' change of average temperature by substracting min value from max value. I chose max and min, because globally temperature is increasing and max temperature must be recent, and min is not.
yclean %>% group_by(City, year) %>% summarise(ave = mean(AverageTemperature)) %>% group_by(City) %>% na.omit() %>% summarise(diff = max(ave) - min(ave)) %>% arrange(desc(diff))

#3-1 Saint Petersburg

#Jaehyun Song
# With cities we share, we proceed visualization. To get identical visualized graphs, I  made visualization code for each city.
# We visualized every city's tendency of temperature overall and by season, and then find evident changes.
# After finding changes, we individually searched more about city's economical growth or industrialization to find if it affected temperature.

# I searched cities in Europe and Austrailia.

#Europe was heavily influenced by World War II. World War II was a war that lasted from September 1, 1939 to September 2, 1945. At this time, economic growth was delayed, and industries were also slow to grow. So it's more noticeable that the graph of temperature rise in this period is slowing compared to other continents. After the war, active reconstruction is made, and with the population exploding, enormous consumption begins to take place, followed by an increase in production, and the economy expands.
#Industrialization began around the 1850s, when rapidly developing St. Petersburg, Berlin and London saw temperatures rise by 1860-1940s or drop by less than 0.25 degrees. But in Rome, where the industry did not develop, and Madrid, which has fallen again, falls by about 0.5 degrees during this period. It can be said that industrialization has affected the rest of global warming.



#First, I filtered data by city I want to process with.
city <- yclean %>% filter(City=="Saint Petersburg") %>% na.omit()

#Because there is too much data due to data is recorded eavry month, I grouped by 'year' and made average temperature per year. 
# Then I used ggplot to visualize.I used geom_line to show how average temperature per year fluctuated
# Also I made regression line to show the general change. I thinkened regression line so we can easily visualize the tendency.
# The horizontal line is to show the average temperature during whole period. We can see when temperature started to go over that temperature.
city %>% group_by(year) %>% summarise(ave = mean(AverageTemperature)) %>% na.omit() %>% 
  ggplot() + geom_line(col="dark grey") + aes(x=year, y=ave) + geom_smooth(col='Red', se=F, lwd=1.7)+
  geom_hline(yintercept=mean(city$AverageTemperature), col='pink', lwd=1.3)+
  labs(title = "Trend of the Yearly Average Temperature", subtitle="Saint Petersburg", x= "Date(year)", y="Temperature(C)")+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1860, 2013, 20))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

#This code is to see tendency of average temperature per year grouped by seasons. Code is similar with the above, but facet_wrap function is added to show 4 seasons.
city %>% group_by(season, year) %>% summarise(ave = mean(AverageTemperature)) %>% na.omit() %>% 
  ggplot() + geom_line(col="dark grey") + aes(x=year, y=ave) + geom_smooth(col='light blue', se=F)+
  labs(title = "Trend of the Yearly Average Temperature by Season", subtitle="Saint Petersburg", x= "Date(year)", y="Temperature(C)")+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1860, 2013, 20))+
  facet_wrap(~season)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

#The difference between the highest and lowest is 5.26 degrees, and it has increased by about 2.5 degrees over the period we observed. Industrialization began in 1861, and the temperature rises steeply in line with the industrialization period. Global warming has made it one degree hotter, and the 2.5 degree rise at this time is a lot higher.

#The difference between the highest and lowest is 3.98 degrees, and it has increased by about 2 degrees over the period we surveyed. In 1848, railways were built, and industrialization was carried out. It underwent a rapid industrialization process since the mid-19th century. Industrialization itself was highly deviated by region, but in the late 19th century, the proportion of industrial population in the entire population increased rapidly. Moreover, textiles and leather industries, which are traditional industries, were relatively stagnant, while in new industries such as coal, steel, chemicals and electricity, rapid growth was repeated along with the introduction and spread of modern production organizations. During the period 1873-1900, the number of modern factory workers surged from 1.8 million to 5.7 million, exceeding 60 percent of the total industrial population. At the same time, the centralization phenomenon of large companies leading production was noticeable. The industrial population began to explode in 1880, and temperatures have been rising since 1880.

#Kim Yoon Ji
#Similar graph with above, but faceted with seasons (3~5: Spring, 6~8: Summer, 9~11: Autumn, 12~2: Winter)
rio %>% group_by(season, year) %>% summarise(ave = mean(AverageTemperature)) %>% na.omit() %>% 
  ggplot() + geom_line(col="dark grey") + aes(x=year, y=ave) + geom_smooth(col='light blue', se=F)+

  facet_wrap(~season)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

As Brazil industrialized roughly from 1900s, the temperature graphs show the increase from 1900s. Though the industrialization is a factor of climate change, urban expansion is at least partly responsible. Between 1960 and 2015, Rio? greater metropolitan area grew by roughly 7 million people and has seen development spread into areas that used to be rural or forested. Since common building materials like asphalt, steel, concrete, and brick retain more heat than vegetation, land development elevates surface and, to a lesser degree, air temperatures. Meanwhile, the vehicles, factories, and air conditioning units that come with urbanization pump even more heat into the urban atmosphere. Therefore, increased humaon activity due to population explosion and the consequence emission and heat can be the significant reason for Rio de Janeiros climate change. So Paulo is also the city of Brazil and its geographical location is close to Rio de Janeiro, the reason for its climate change might not be different from Rio de Janeiros.

#Forecasting 2014~2020 temperature from the temperature between 2005~2013

We used time-series and forecast packages to forecast future temperature by using past days patterns. We made a graph of forecasted data and merged with the graph of actual temperature data measured between 2014 and 2020 May. Then we compared those two graphs and saw the difference between them.

library(forecast)
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'quantmod':
##   method            from
##   as.zoo.data.frame zoo

#South Korea - Seoul

#Kim Yerin
#I got the real temperature in Seoul data from the Meteorological Administration. #(https://data.kma.go.kr/stcs/grnd/grndTaList.do?pgmNo=70)
#Read Seoul's real temperature data and save it into 'RealTempInSeoul'
RealTempInSeoul <- read.csv("SeoulTemp.csv")
#Since this is the Korea data I change columnnames to English to work in R.
colnames(RealTempInSeoul) <- c("dt","location","average","low","high")
#Make the dataframe with selecting needed column 'dt', 'average' and mutating columns 'when'(by changing the data type to date from dt column), 'year'(by admitting the year function of lubridate to when column). 
RealTempInSeoul <- RealTempInSeoul %>% select(dt, average) %>% mutate(When = as.Date(dt, format="%Y-%m-%d"), year=year(When))

#Extract only Seoul's climate data of 'yclean' from 2005 and save it in 'seoul'.
seoul <- yclean %>% filter(City=="Seoul" & year >= 2005) %>% na.omit() 
#Summarise average temperature of each year and save the summary into 'seoul_avgtemp'.
seoul_avgtemp <- summarise(group_by(seoul,year),avg_temp = mean(AverageTemperature))
#Make the 'avg_temp' column of 'seoul_avgtemp' dataframe into time series and save it as 'seoul_.ts'. I made a time series in yearly frequency to draw the annual average temperature line and inspect the overall increase.
seoul_.ts <- ts(seoul_avgtemp$avg_temp, start = 2005, end = 2013, frequency = 1)
#Make the 'AverageTemperature' column of 'seoul' dataframe into time series and save it as 'seoul.ts'. I made a time series in monthly frequency from 2005 to 2013 to find seasonality.
seoul.ts <- ts(seoul$AverageTemperature, start = 2005, end = 2013, frequency = 12)

#Make 'average' column of 'RealTempInSeoul' dataframe and save it as 'RSeoul.ts' as well.
RSeoul.ts <- ts(RealTempInSeoul$average, start = 2013, end = 2020, frequency = 12)

#I used average and seasonal naive model for forecasting. Since our time series have seasonal repetition, we made the time series in monthly frequency.**
seoul.train <- window(seoul.ts, end = 2013)
seoul.average <- meanf(seoul.train, h = 84)
seoul.snaive <- snaive(seoul.train, h = 84)

#Plotting graph of past temperature and average of all observations for all future predictions
plot(seoul.average, ylim=c(-10,40), col = "dark grey",main="From 2005 Temperature Forecasting", sub="South Korea - Seoul")
#Draw a line of Seasonal naive in green
lines(seoul.snaive$mean, col = "green", lty = 1, lwd=1.5)
#Add the real temperature data between 2014 and 2020 in red
lines(RSeoul.ts, col = "red", lty = 1, lwd =2)
#Draw a linear regression of past temperature data 'seoul' in black
abline(lm(avg_temp~year, data = seoul_avgtemp), col = "black", lwd=2)
#Add annual average temperature of past temperature data in orange.
lines(seoul_.ts, col = "orange", lwd = 3)
#Show the legend of each graph element

legend(2005,40,c("RealTemp","snaive","referenceline","YearAvgTemp"), cex=0.7, col=c("red","green","black","orange"),pch=1, lty=1,lwd=2)

**) Reason why we made the time series in monthly frequency: At first, we try to group by the year and drew the line graph of temperature from 1980 to 2013 and predict how the climate would be from 2014 to 2020. but when we code this and use the seasonal naive method, the line appear as linear, which makes us hard to compare our prediction with real data. As the seasonality is represented monthly, we think that not grouping by the year and drew the graph by the month let us show the seasonality more clearly and compare with real data easily. Then, the bin width of x-axis became too small to inspect the prediction, so we limit the x value start from January 2005.

  1. Comparing our prediction and the real temperature data: There is no significant difference between predicted temperature(green graph) and real temperature(red graph) in Seoul. Since there was no special industrial events or disasters to change the climate in Seoul between 2013 and 2020.
